Mr. Belford so much obliged Miss Howe by Mr. Belford steadiness, equity, and dispatch, and by Mr. Belford readines to contribute to the directed collection, that Miss Howe voluntarily entered into a correspondence with Mr. Belford, as the representative of Miss Howe beloved friend.
In the course of which, Mr. Belford communicated to Miss Howe (in confidence) the Letters which passed between Mr. Belford and Mr. Lovelace, and, by Colonel Morden's consent, those which passed between that gentleman and Colonel Morden.
Colonel Morden sent with the first parcel of letters which Colonel Morden had transcribed out of short-hand for Miss Howe, a letter to Mr. Hickman, dated the 16th of September; in which he expresses he as follows:                 he then excuses Mr. Lovelace, as a good-natured man, with all he faults: and gives instances of he still greater freedoms with he.
