Miss Howe, in hers of the 20th, acknowleging the receipt of the letters, and papers, and legacies, sent with Mr. Belford's letter to Mr. Hickman, assures Mr. Belford,             Mr. Belford had mentioned with compassion the distresses of the Harlowe family√ë                  Mr. Belford, in Mr. Belford answer, promises, that she shall be the purchaser of the jewels, if she shall be the purchaser of the jewels come into Mr. Belford hands.
Mr. Belford acquaints she, that the family had given Col. Morden the keys of all that belonged to the dear departed: That the unhappy mother had (as the Will allows) ordered a piece of needlework to be set aside for the unhappy mother, and had desired Mrs. Norton to get the little book of <i>Meditations</i> transcribed, and to let the unhappy mother have the original, as it was all of the unhappy mother dear daughter's hand-writing; and as it might, when the unhappy mother could bear to look into it, administer consolation to the unhappy mother.
And that the unhappy mother had likewise reserved for the unhappy mother the unhappy mother picture in the Vandyke taste.
Mr. Belford sends with this letter to Miss Howe the lady's memorandum-book; and promises to send Miss Howe the lady's memorandum-book copies of the several posthumous letters.
Mr. Belford tells Miss Howe the lady's memorandum-book, that Mr. Lovelace being upon the recovery, Mr. Belford had inclosed the posthumous letter directed for Mr. Belford to Lord M. that Lord M. Lordship might give his Lordship to Mr. Belford, or not, as Mr. Belford should find Mr. Belford could bear his Lordship.
